\begin_layout Subsection
Scanning probe microscopy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scanning probe microscopy (SPM) is a series of techniques to produce detailed
 characterization over a 3D surface.
 A long, sharp needle of material is held perpendicular to the plane of
 the surface allowing the SPM to measure the interactions of the tip and
 surface.
 The tip is traced across the plane forming a map of the tip-surface interaction
s.
 Piezoelectric crystals attached to the tip let the tip move in over short
 distances in any direction with fine precision.
 This is often combined with additional motors, such as a stepper motor,
 can move the entire piezoelectric crystals and tip structure over larger
 distances but sacrifice precision to do so.
 With an isolated environment, engineered to shield the tip from external
 noise, and a sharp tip, a SPM map can provide details down to the atomic
 level.
 There are many different varieties of SPM that measure quantities like
 magnetic field, density of states, and spin; and far too many to discuss
 here, so only a brief overview of the most relevant are below.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Atomic-force-microscope"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the the typical setup of most SPM microscopes.
\end_layout

