\begin_layout Standard
Caution must be used when using PFM to identify ferroelectric behaviors
 as multiple phenomena cause similar responses.
 A short list of some of the most common follows, and they are discussed
 in depth elsewhere
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "balke2015differentiating,vasudevan2017ferroelectric"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The voltage bias from the tip can inject charged particles into the surface
 of the material, and while they typically dissipate after several hours
 in an insulator, the injected trapped charges will appear very similar
 to writing remnant states and hysteresis loops in a ferroelectric.
 Large currents from the tip to the surface can also cause joule heating,
 distorting the lattice and can be again picked up from a subsequent PFM
 scan.
 Strain gradients from the tip putting pressure on thin crystals can reverse
 polarization, the flexoelectric effect.
 The voltage bias from a PFM tip can move ions in a crystal within a unit
 cell or between cells, the former a characteristic of ferroelectric dipoles
 while the latter is ionic conduction.
 Both cause distortion of the crystal structure and are virtually indistinguisha
ble from each other by PFM.
 At high enough electric fields, amplified by the sharp point of the PFM
 tip, the surface chemistry can be altered through electrochemical reactions,
 especially with oxides.
 These changes can be either reversible or irreversible, even within the
 same material using different voltages.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "balke2015differentiating,vasudevan2017ferroelectric"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 There are other less common pit-falls not listed here, and ways to mitigate
 some of the problems mentioned, but both are beyond the scope of what should
 be discussed here.
 PFM should almost never be taken as complete proof that a material is ferroelec
tric, but still can be an excellent tool to used to study properties of
 ferroelectric materials such as domain propagation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optical second harmonic generation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A process frequently used to study crystal structure and material properties
 is optical second harmonic generation (SHG).
 A single frequency laser is used to measure the crystal medium.
 As can be inferred from its name, pairs of photons interact with the medium
 and generate photons at twice the initial frequency.
 Keeping to the electric field contribution, this nonlinear process is described
 mathematically as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(2\omega\right)=\chi^{\left(2\right)}E\left(\omega\right)E\left(\omega\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the induced dipole per unit volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 the electric field from a photon with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 the three-rank nonlinear susceptibility tensor of the material
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ma2020richinformation"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 If we approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 in a multipole expansion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi^{\left(2\right)}\left(\omega,\vec{q}\right)\ensuremath{\approx}\chi_{ED}^{\left(2\right)}\left(\omega\right)+\chi_{EQ}^{\left(2\right)}\left(\omega\right)+O\left(\vec{q}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the wave vector of the incident photon, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{ED}$
\end_inset

 is the electric dipole contribution, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{EQ}$
\end_inset

 electric quadrupole
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "denev2011probing"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Typically the quadrupole response is much smaller than the dipole, though
 it can still be measured and gives valuable information about some crystal
 structures, but we can neglect it for this discussion.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{EQ}$
\end_inset

 tensor is constrained by several symmetries giving it just 10 independent
 parameters, but most importantly it goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{EQ,ijk}=0$
\end_inset

 in a centrosymmetric system.
 As ferroelectricity can only exist in non-centrosymmetric systems, SHG
 response is an important test to see if a crystal is a possible ferroelectric
 material.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "denev2011probing"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 While it can not identify ferroelectricity, SHG can quickly screen out
 non-ferroelectric materials, and can measure 2D crystals down to a single
 layer
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "leisgang2018optical"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
