\begin_layout Standard
The LOR/SPR negative resist stack is easy to use and allows for high resolution
 patterns down to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mu m$
\end_inset

.
 Before any resist is added the substrate is given a dehydration bake of
 
\begin_inset Formula $115C$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $60s$
\end_inset

 to remove any water.
 A layer of LOR-2A is statically deposited as the first layer of the stack.
 The substrate is then spun at 
\begin_inset Formula $4000RPM$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $45s$
\end_inset

 reducing the LOR-2A to a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim200nm$
\end_inset

 thick coating.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lorand"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Finally we bake it at 
\begin_inset Formula $180C$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $60s$
\end_inset

 on a hot plate to remove some solvent.
 Next a layer of SPR-3012 is dynamically dispensed at 900RPM.
 The substrate is then sped up and spun again at 
\begin_inset Formula $4000RPM$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $45s$
\end_inset

 flattening the SPR-3012 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1.3\mu m$
\end_inset

 thick.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "megaposit"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 This is then baked for 
\begin_inset Formula $95C$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $60s$
\end_inset

